<br>
I think you are perhaps skewing the dictionary-definition of &quot;god&quot;, or using the word &quot;god&quot; from a different context that does not pertain to this kind of discussion (i.e. a religious one).  Yes, one can refer to money or energy--even Elvis--as god (I even had a crush in high school whom I referred to as &quot;God&quot;), but used in that context it does not pertain to a discussion or debate about the existence of a supernatural, omniscient, &quot;incorporeal devine&quot; being.  That's like using ovaries to talk about omelettes--yes, they both have to do with &quot;eggs&quot; but they're not the same thing.  To confuse worship of a deity with an unhealthy obsession or pathology (would make an interesting topic on its own) but does nothing to further the argument that there is or may be god.<br>
<br>
-Simone <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dbc67>DBC67</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Avatar of Reason</span><br>  Posts: 285<br> <font color=#3333ff>(6/19/03 11:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=214.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.rune-stone.net/Pitt/avatar.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What do you call an atheist?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Since you said that there are effectively an infinite number of things in the universe that could be gods, i is a set which is infinitely large. For argument sake, let’s say that the probability of being god for each thing is the same. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Fun with numbers, you make an infinite number of things in the unuiverse and make it infinitely likely that one is a god, of course it will work out that atheism is wrong.  I however would have made it infinitely <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>UN</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->likely</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that one was a god.  It is all in your assumptions though when dealing with irrational numbers expect irrational results.  Next you have equated god to an idol and are now claiming that I say idols don't exist.  Interesting application of equivication.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>God</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
1a) A being conceived as the perfect, omnipotent, omniscient originator and ruler of the universe, the principal object of faith and worship in monotheistic religions. <br>
1b) The force, effect, or a manifestation or aspect of this being. <br>
2) A being of supernatural powers or attributes, believed in and worshiped by a people, especially a male deity thought to control some part of nature or reality. <br>
3) An image of a supernatural being; an idol. <br>
4) One that is worshiped, idealized, or followed: Money was their god. <br>
5) A very handsome man. <br>
6) A powerful ruler or despot.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> You will be hard pressed to find an atheist who disbelieves in the last three, and harder pressed to find one who believes in the first 3.  There is no supernatural component to money.  There is no attribution to money of the creation of the universe.  Applying your logic, there is no such thing as a true atheist, because to be a true atheist you would have to disbelieve in purely natural things that some person somewhere has decided to worship.  This is a poorly framed argument at best.  You are equating it to absurdity.  Atheists do not believe in supernatural gods.  We are not claiming money doesn't exist or that some people focus on it excessively.  An idol being worshiped is merely the physical representation of a supernatural being for the purposes of directing and focusing worship.  Not a material thing itself.  I submit that your friend who worships money, in actuallity worships the power that money brings and if he mistakenly attributes supernatural force (money will make me beautiful, money makes the planet rotate) then it is NOT the god he thinks it is.  It is only small bits of paper and metal with no individual power at all.  The crux of the distinction being that the first 3 ARE gods, and the last three are LIKE gods, and thus get called that and consequently appear in the dictionary under that heading.<br>
<br>
I have yet to meet an atheist who claims &quot;Yeah well that Yahweh does NOT exist, so I am an atheist, but that Allah guy though I don't know about.&quot;  That is an absurdity.  People who worship a god that exludes other gods, xians for example, then become part of your set of pseudo atheists because they don't believe in mithra or vishnu.  That isn't a pseudo atheist, that is a NONatheist.  Heh, and you say MY view of atheism is skewed. LOL!<br>
<br>
The argumentation of being an atheist is that we do not believe in supernatural gods.  To disprove this, someone has to roll out a god.  This necessitates us specifically evaluating the god rolled out and disproving it to remain an atheist.  Much simpler and cleaner than you would represent.  So, as I said, if you roll something out and call it a god and it exists, then that thing is not a god.  Call money a god if you like, there is nothing supernatural about it, it is not a god.  You may treat it like a god, but treating it as something and being that thing are two different things.  I treat my daughter like a princess, but she has no claim to any thrones.<br>
<br>
Sorry if you feel sarcasm is an ad hominem, but to be an ad hominem that attack would have to be 'to the man' for example if I had called you an idiot or a moron.  This is however a no-holds-barred forum, so if it bothers you, then you'll need to get over it.  I come here because it entertains me, not to get anyones respect.  I don't really give a damn if you respect me or not, or call me an idiot or not.<br>
