<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is no supernatural component to money. There is no attribution to money of the creation of the universe.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
There are religions that do not have supernatural gods, they have natural gods.  They also don't credit the creation of the universe to the gods.  For example, the wiccan coven that I visited does not believe that their gods can do everything.  They believe in nature as god, and nature by definition is natural.  When asked about the creation of the universe, almost all of them replied, &quot;I don't know how the universe came into being.  Personally, I don't need to know.  It's here, that's what matters most.&quot;  Now correct me if I'm wrong, but isn't wicca recognized as a religion?  Some of the larger organizations do get the tax exempt status that other religious institutions get.  This would suggest that, at very least, the government recognizes wicca as a religion.  Christian organizations recognize it as a rival religion, so this would suggest that the religious community also recognizes it as a religion.<br>
<br>
Funny that this religion is almost always missed when atheists try to reinforce their disbelief in god(s).<br>
