<br>
Furthermore, athiests do not share common traits aside from disbelief in gods that can be labeled as a philosophy.  You can be an atheist wiccan, and atheist humanist, an atheist naturalist, an atheist lunatic, anything.  There are even atheist xians.  Atheism is a property, not a philosophy.  You can disbelieve in gods because the evidence does not support it, or you can disbelieve in gods because your dog told you there weren't any.  Both are equally atheist.<br>
<br>
Lastly, your fun with numbers prank.  Yes I read your post, I even quoted from it directly where you said the set was infinitely large, then assigned a non-zero probability that any one of them may be god. This can only yeild one result, one of them must be god.  Any infinite set with a non-zero probability will always yeild such a result.  This inevitably follows from generalized, oversimplified or poorly chosen variable values.  Why not try my probability?  Zero.  Then with an infinite set, you still get the same result as a finite set.  Zero.  There is no god.  Pascal's wager and others like it are philosophically immature and a waste of time.  You can dress it up with calculus, but it is still the same bet, and still loses.  Why not roll out a god for us to measure.  If you can, you may just convert us. <p>DBC67<br>
