From my experiences, the problem is that most people cannot fathom a non-authoritarian religion.  It's also that when thinking of religion, people aren't used to the idea that there isn't necesarily one path that is right for everybody, but path that is right for each individual.  Even your average atheist is of the opinion that their path is the right one and that everyone that is not on their path is merely being self-deceptive.  Other than that, what is so different about wicca as a religion?  We have groups of like minded believers who gather at regular intervals to worship the deitites.(also known as covens)  We have generally one or two people who lead the group during these meetings.(High priestess and/or high priest)  We have religious holidays, and a rule of conduct,&quot;An it harm none, do what thou will.&quot;  Or are you trying to say that those two major differences listed above are enough to differentiate wicca from most forms of religion?  If you are trying to say that, I'd have to agree.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Although wiccan organizations have been active in the legal matters pretaining to the rights of it's followers, it would not be fair to say that this was the original reason for forming these organizations.  Some of them formed because they knew that the public interest would be focused on them for awhile after having been established, and that is a good way to increase awareness of the path without trying to force their beliefs upon others.<br>
<br>
Your post brings up a question that I was wanting to ask.  Please let me know if it would be better to place this in a new thread.<br>
Pretty much all of us are aware that the two extremes to religious faiths are the following.  <br>
1)Fanatic theists who believe that their belief is the only right way, and anything that violates the supreme sanctity of the word of god will be punished severely, whether it be burning in hell for all eternity, being stoned to death by a practitioner of the faith, or something completely different.<br>
2)Fanatic atheists who believe that anyone who believes that anyone who believes in deities are merely in a state of self-denial, and should wake up and see the world for what it really is.  They generally will not hesitate to call people idiots/stupid/ignorant when those people stand up for their religious beliefs.<br>
Now most people are not fanatical, but they still like to remain near these two extrtemes.  My question is whether or not there is a happy medium.  A place where theists and atheists can see eye to eye without carrying all the stereotypical bias of their particular beliefs.<br>
<br>
