<br>
I disagree with your assessment that everyone falls to an extreme.  I would say the bulk of the bell-curve is just like that, in the middle, like a bell curve (sorry, standard gaussian distribution for you math purists.)  The one thing I have noticed in conversation with theists is that they really HAVEN’T examined their theology very closely.  Typically, they are whatever their parents were, or some derivative close to, or in the odd case whatever their spouse is if they weren’t too concerned.  Once in a while there is the reactionary who went far afield from their parents, but consistently they seldom hold a critical examination of their faith.  They just like how it “feels.”  Contrary to my appearance here, I am not a bristling rabid atheist IRL.  I actually do the books for a church and they are constantly asking my business advice and inviting my family to their events and count us as members of their congregation (even to the point of harassing me to join the choir) despite our being clear that we are atheists.  I have many friends of diverse beliefs and we are mutually respectful.  As here I do not back down in the face of challenge, but unlike here I am more sensitive to the fragility of some peoples theology and will stop (if they do) and not try and shred their system.  Among my closest friends are a buddhist, a satanist, a baptist and several atheists.<br>
<br>
No, I see the extremes as just that, extreme.  Not many there at all.<br>
 <p>DBC67<br>
