Just because a god is not omnipotent doesn’t mean he/she is not supernatural. If the deity in question defies the laws of physics or natural laws, then isn’t s/he supernatural by definition???(example—providing psychic guidance, invisible beings not limited by space and time…) I am very good friends with a few different types of pagans (yes, there ARE many types of pagans too, not all of which involve covens) and none of them believes a typical xian-type creation myth, nor do they buy the patriarch in the sky type god, but all believe in supernatural beings of some sort and often practice rituals to “tap into energies”, “communicate with spirit guides” or “draw down the moon”.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Now correct me if I'm wrong, but isn't wicca recognized as a religion? Some of the larger organizations do get the tax exempt status that other religious institutions get. This would suggest that, at very least, the government recognizes wicca as a religion. Christian organizations recognize it as a rival religion, so this would suggest that the religious community also recognizes it as a religion.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->You weren’t addressing me, but firstly I don’t give a flying turd what xians recognize and the gov’t gives the same tax exempt status to other “religions” like Satanism, Buddhism and UUA that are either inclusive of or largely secular/philosophical systems as opposed to those involving the supernatural.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Funny that this religion is almost always missed when atheists try to reinforce their disbelief in god(s).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not by me. In fact I make the effort to use a lower case g and plural when discussing this issue, especially with xians who DO make the assumption that theism=monotheism and that atheists are just anti-xian. Rest assured I find Wicca just as implausible and irrational as xianity and your gods just as false and mythical, and I am not unusual. <br>
<br>
Interesting that YOU posted this though-<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Pretty much all of us are aware that the two extremes to religious faiths are the following. <br>
1)Fanatic theists who believe that their belief is the only right way, and anything that violates the supreme sanctity of the word of god will be punished severely, whether it be burning in hell for all eternity, being stoned to death by a practitioner of the faith, or something completely different.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Now Phoenix if it is so important to you that the word theist not be limited to xians then why the use of all xian themes here (hell, stoning)? It certainly seems like you are using the word theist synonymously with xian (leaving pagans out) or was this intentionally done to imply only non-pagans are &quot;fanatic theists&quot;?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>2)Fanatic atheists who believe that anyone who believes that anyone who believes in deities are merely in a state of self-denial, and should wake up and see the world for what it really is. They generally will not hesitate to call people idiots/stupid/ignorant when those people stand up for their religious beliefs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Oh boy more stereotyping!! <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A place where theists and atheists can see eye to eye without carrying all the stereotypical bias of their particular beliefs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well a good first step would be to stop lumping all pagans together (pagan is a term as broad as heathen, atheist etc. and implies NO specific, pre-set dogma), not use the word fanatic when you probably mean fundamentalist and stop accusing large groups of people of name-calling without any evidence. Might also help to not say we are all either extremists or tending toward an extreme position. I, for one, am tired of being defined by the fringe and this type of talk just encourages that. <br>
<br>
I believe common ground is possible only among parties that desire it and can be tolerant and respectful of other belief systems. For many theists this is very possible. For those practicing more intolerant dogmatic version of theism, namely xianity, it is much, much more difficult.<br>
<br>
ST<br>
