Finally, DL.<br>
While I was an atheist, my sole goal in life was to gather knowledge.  The more and more time passed, the more I withdrew into myself, and the more I learned.  The only problem was that I was seeking knowledge, not wisdom.  Then I became interested in wicca.  I learnt about it in my search for knowledge, and immediately began to appreciate some of its teachings.(At least relative to some of the other religious teachings that I had been exposed to.)  Soon after, while discussing it with a friend, she told me that she was a wiccan.  Through her, I met with a couple covens to see what specific beliefs they possessed, and in the end I was asked to join one of the covens.  I enjoyed the time I spent with the coven, and I agreed with their beliefs, so I accepted their invitation.  We have official meetings about 5 times a month, plus on the sabbats.  We also get together on a regular basis for a 'night out on the town'.  That's what I get from my belief system.  I get the social interaction that I would not normally get due to my personality type.  I get a group of friends that are closer to me than my family.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=doublelatte>Double Latte</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Got Milk?</span><br>  Posts: 200<br> <font color=#3333ff>(6/20/03 8:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=214.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What do you call an atheist?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>We have official meetings about 5 times a month, plus on the sabbats. We also get together on a regular basis for a 'night out on the town'. That's what I get from my belief system. I get the social interac